Collection.Caption: Eliminating enemies is secondary to protecting our battery carriers.
When the batteries become available, rally all forces and defend the carriers.
Getting those batteries up the hill will take teamwork. Don't be afraid to hand them off.
The paracausal batteries are of vital importance. Guard them with care.
Once we control those batteries, it may take more than one of us to get up the hill.
The paracausal energy in the batteries will confer an aura of power, for a time.
After we install those batteries, drop everything and open fire.
The batteries are key to stabilizing the Blind Well. Stay close to the carriers, and don't stop shooting.

Sequence.Caption: Hold off the hostiles until we gain access to the batteries. Once they appear, you'll have to install them manually.
They're extremely heavy, so I suggest you work together.

Collection.Caption: The batteries grant an aura of power. Stay close to them for maximum effect.
The batteries are too heavy to carry while fighting. Stay close to the carriers and watch their backs!
As soon as we get access to those batteries, start hauling. Take turns if you have to.
The Ley Lines must be stabilized. Install the batteries to end this invasion.
Xivu Arath claws at the fabric of this reality, forcing her way through. Protect the compass!
My Corsairs report increased Taken activity. Retrieve the compass and assume defensive positions.
Xivu Arath's forces have regrouped. We can't let them take the Blind Well!
I sense Taken rifts condensing. Xivu Arath's army will be here soon. Keep the compass safe, Guardian.
Grab your compass, Guardian. We’ve got Taken inbound.

Sequence.Caption: Xivu Arath is sending her strongest lieutenants to secure the Blind Well.
We can't allow them to establish a beachhead for the Hive!

Collection.Caption: Taken forces gather at the edges of this reality. They are coming.
We’ve got Taken incoming. Secure your compass before they arrive.
Make sure you keep your compass safe. Things are about to get loud.

Sequence.Caption: The Taken are fleeing. I feel the tears in this reality slowly beginning to mend.
But this will not be their last trespass. We must remain vigilant.
Xivu Arath's consolidation of Hive forces is almost complete. Even those on Luna now fall under her command.
It makes me wonder why everyone sees Savathûn as the bigger threat.
The Taken rifts are receding, and the area is secure.
Until we reveal the true voice behind the Darkness, none of us can be secure.
We shut down the Taken rifts, and the Ley Lines are stabilizing.
But until we reassemble Queen Mara's coven, we're just plugging leaks.
Just like streams of water, Ley Lines can be polluted.
Xivu Arath will use them to poison the Blind Well if she can. Stay vigilant.
You can carry a lot of weight, Petra. I'm impressed.
I've had no choice. For years, the Dreaming City rested on my shoulders.
Good work, Guardian. Paracausal energy readings are back to nominal levels.
The Taken energy has dissipated… for now.
The Taken threaten not just territory, but the very fabric of our reality.
And they'll start with the Blind Well. We have to close down any Taken rifts.
Xivu Arath is sending in Taken as shock troops, and holding Hive forces in reserve.
She hopes that the Taken will destabilize the Blind Well enough for a full invasion.
If the Taken can use the Ascendant Plane to attack the Blind Well, why not just seal it off once and for all?
Ceding control of the Ley Lines would cut us off from Queen Mara's throne world.
And losing Eleusinia would end all hope of one day lifting the curse on the Dreaming City.
For a long time, we thought that the Blind Well led to your throne world alone, Queen Mara.
That used to be the case, until our new Techeuns cleverly repurposed it.
In doing so, they opened the Blind Well to the rest of the Ascendant Plane… and Xivu Arath.
Queen Mara, if your ritual goes according to plan, what will happen to Savathûn?
Without her worm, she'll be powerless.
That seems like a waste. Imagine how much intel she could provide.
To us… or to you?

Collection.Caption: Xivu Arath's forces have infested this area. Their Taken rifts are destabilizing the Ley Lines, making alignment impossible.
Taken rifts are destabilizing the area. We can't allow them to disrupt the Ley Lines.

Sequence.Caption: The Taken are massing for another attack. They just can't take a hint.
Xivu Arath won't let them. They're driven by an insatiable need to heed her commands.
I saw the same thing with the cryptoliths on the Shore. So many minds ruined by her need to dominate.
The strong forcing the weak to fight on their behalf. It's the oldest story in the world.
The Taken are mounting another attack. Push them back before they get entrenched, Guardian.
Does this ever end? Do Guardians really spend all their time going from one fight to the next?
That's the job, Crow. Most of Vanguard leadership has been at it for centuries.
No wonder Saladin is so jaded.

Collection.Caption: The batteries are operational and paracausal energy readings are nominal. Good work, Guardian.
My readings show that all hostile forces have retreated, and the Blind Well is safe.

Sequence.Caption: Energy readings have stabilized.
The Guardian's compass has guided us faithfully yet again.

Collection.Caption: Good work installing the batteries, Guardian. The regulators are functioning normally.

Sequence.Caption: The energy contained in those batteries are attractive targets for the Taken and Scorn alike.
We need to keep a close eye on them.
Feels good to be back in the fight. I've been on the sidelines for too long.
From what I saw, the Guardian did all the work.
I never knew something as small as those batteries could be so dense.
And I thought Glint was heavy for his size.
With the regulators powered up, the Blind Well will be easier to travel through.
And easier to invade.
Carrying those batteries felt… empowering.
The radiation they emit is largely unstudied. I wouldn't hold them for too long.
The Scorn never learn. They'd be well-served to find their Ether elsewhere.
They're driven less by hunger, and more by a knife at their backs.
Well played, Guardian. I'm sure Crow wishes he could share in this victory.
If that were true, he'd be here right now.
Once we have our Techeuns back, holding this area will be much easier.
Thank you for all your aid.
The Scorn are broken, and all that Ether is lost.
Better to lose the Ether than the Blind Well. Good work, Guardian.
Scans show that this sector is clear. Unfortunately, Xivu Arath's forces are already amassing elsewhere.
As long as we have Savathûn, she won't stop coming.
As much as the Scorn disgust me, I still feel a strange pity for them.
I wonder why.
Good work shutting down the Scorn, Guardian.
The timing of their mission is suspicious. Is this coordination with Xivu Arath, or mere coincidence?
I hate to waste so much good Ether, but anything to get the Scorn out of the area.
War is always a waste of good resources. Get used to it.
I know it's hard to destroy good Ether when the House of Light goes hungry, but sacrifices must be made.
Mithrax-kell would understand.

Collection.Caption: The Scorn are here for the Ether. Destroy it when it’s released, and the Scorn will break.
We must not allow the Scorn to harvest this Ether. Destroy it!
Keep an eye on the harvesters. They'll indicate when the Ether is about to be released.
Ether gives life. Let its destruction bring death to the Scorn.
Watch the harvesters to time the Ether release. Let's send these Scorn back empty-handed.
Once the Servitors release the Ether, destroy it before it reaches the harvesters.
The Servitors can't be damaged, but the Ether they release can. Destroy it, and the Scorn.
Target the Ether when it's released. The Scorn can't poison the Ley Lines without it.

Sequence.Caption: The Scorn will try to harvest Ether from these dead Servitors.
The Servitors will release the Ether at regular intervals. Keep an eye on the harvester to anticipate it.
Once the Ether is released, destroy it before it gets to the harvester!

Collection.Caption: It pains me to say it, but we need to target the Ether coming from the Servitors. It's better off destroyed than in the hands of the Scorn.
Keep watch on the harvesters—they'll indicate when the Servitors are going to release their Ether. Once the Ether is exposed, destroy it.
We'll have a window of opportunity after the Servitors release their Ether, but before it reaches the harvesters. That's when we strike.
Those Servitors are dead, but they've still got reserve Ether inside. We've got to destroy it before the Scorn can collect it.

Sequence.Caption: Aside from her unfortunate conversation with Crow, Savathûn has been a model prisoner. Don't you find that odd?
Savathûn can scheme all she wants. Her lies end at the point of my knife.
If things… don't go as expected with the ritual, we should consider calling on Empress Caiatl.
After the destruction of her homeworld, she has more cause to fight Xivu Arath than anyone.
It's true. And we know that if Xivu Arath has her way, Earth and the Reef will be next.
I can barely feel them. My Techeuns, lost between realms.
But beyond that, in the background… there is something else.
It is not Xivu Arath. It is not simple Hive madness.
It is as though the space between the stars has been waiting. Watching.
And it hates us.
Another successful mission, my queen. Your coven is almost reassembled.
Well done, Petra.
I know your path has not been easy in my absence. Your dedication these years past has been exemplary.
But I fear the hardest part is yet to come. The Black Fleet will push us all to the limit before the end.
I will not fail you, my queen. I am your Wrath, always.
I do not doubt it, even for a second.
We've met success, my queen. We're one step closer to getting our lost Techeuns home.
Thank you, Petra.
I want to be there when you draw that worm screaming from Savathûn's carcass.
We will all have our revenge on that day.
Mara… Zavala has asked I raise his concerns.
Yes, his concerns are all I imagine when I hear your voice.
He and Caiatl have questions about the security of Savathûn's crystal prison.
Oh, what should you tell Zavala and his little Cabal?
Tell them I raised a dragon. That I danced down the hilt of Oryx's blade. That I am Queen of the Reef.
You've done it. I can feel relief rippling through the Techeuns.
Let them know we're coming for them.
They know. They can hear my thoughts as if they were their own.
Can you speak like that with all of the Awoken?
Only the ones who are willing to listen.
Thank you, Guardian. With your assistance, we may still be able to recover my remaining Techeuns.
They will have suffered during their imprisonment. Will they be strong enough to complete the ritual?
They must.
There's the Mara I know. Nails still black from brewing queensfoil.
Stains like that never come out.
Wherever Crow is, I hope he knows there are people here who care about him.
As I told you before… now is not the time for this conversation.
I know, Mara. All the same, it's a sentiment I want to state clearly on open comms channels. For anyone who might be monitoring them.
…beep boop.
No games. If he wants to have a conversation, he knows where to find me.
We're so close to reclaiming our city. Soon, I'll put everything back as it was.
That may be harder than you think, Queen Mara.
Some broken things are not so easily mended.
I am Queen of the Reef. And I always will be. Nothing is beyond me.
Once my circle of Techeuns is reassembled, we can strike back at the Black Fleet.
The coming storm will not be deterred by the knowledge of the Vanguard alone.
Knowledge is only part of a winning strategy. Courage, fortitude, and firepower are the rest.
And the Awoken have all of those in abundance.
The Guardian's presence here says otherwise.
The sooner you accept your limitations, the sooner we'll find strength… together.
Crow, this is Ikora. Do you copy?
I'm sorry, Ikora, but Crow would prefer to be alone right now.
I understand. Every Guardian wrestles with their past in their own way.
And Crow has more to wrestle with than most. Don't worry.
I am worried. Even if he eventually accepts who he was, I may never regain his trust.
Oh, Glint. You're his new family. Family always comes around… eventually.
The queen in me always kept Uldren at arm's length, even if the sister in me yearned to be closer.
Seeing him replaced by that guileless fool…
If may speak frankly, my queen, Uldren was always a fool. He was too prideful to earn your acceptance.
Instead, he tried to goad your affection through insubordination.
And now, on the other side of death, he returns as an obedient servant… to another ruler.
The Traveler has a sense of irony, it would seem.
Queen's Wrath, I have a directive for you.
Watching the Guardian work, I have had much time to reflect.
When we are finished with Savathûn, you will prepare a detachment of Paladins to depart for the Tangled Shore.
Of course, my queen.
When I give the order, you and your Paladins will remove the Spider and all of his loyalists from the Reef. Permanently.
We are surrounded by terror. The Dreaming City cries out.
All this conflict, all this death, repeated in an endless feeding cycle to a god of war.
Even this, battling to free Savathûn from her worm, I fear we starve one threat to feed another.
And yet, I have no better solution.
I just have hope. And that is, perhaps, the greatest terror of them all.
Ikora. I wanted to offer you my heartfelt thanks for your composure in this trying time.
You had as much right as any to harbor anger for my brother's deeds. Yet you stayed your hand when you learned of Crow.
The Vanguard firmly believe that who you were before you become a Guardian holds no bearing on your new life.
My anger is my own, and Uldren Sov is dead.
Years ago, I asked your Guardian if they were satisfied by their vengeance. I would ask you the same.
No amount of vengeance can bring back the dead.
On this, we agree.
You did well, Guardian. But I admit that Crow's expertise is missed. He's still a great shot.
I heard that!
Oh, you little pest. Stay off my channel and keep your shell flaps sealed.
Too late!
Hey, buddy, guess what? A certain very angry knife lady says you're an amazing marksman. Best she's ever seen!
He says he doesn't care… but I can tell he does. Thanks, Petra.
Petra, I heard old Crow… before he was Crow… was looking for Mara. Could he have used the Ley Lines to find her?
No. When he… turned, he lost all focus. Rumor is he thought he was being guided by her toward the end.
Could he have willed her image into being somehow?
Whatever happened, I think it’s more complex than that.
I appreciate the Guardian’s talent for finding lost things.
For returning them to you, you mean.
Yes.
Have I mentioned that I appreciate you as well?
We should go. Regroup. The Techeuns aren't going to rescue themselves.
We used to dream about this. Far-off kingdoms. Queens. Witches. Mystic adventures among the stars.
Remember, Crow?
They were only stories. It passed the time.
You wrote them down, like in a book. Always kept the pages on you so Spider wouldn't find them—
Glint. Enough.
My brother was a storyteller too. He spun the most fabulous fables for our people's children.
I have copies in my library, if you like.
That won’t be necessary.
This would go faster if you’d give me an audience with her. She trusts me. She’s smart. We could strategize…
You can speak with Queen Mara any time you like.
I wasn't talking about Queen Mara.
I'll pretend you were, for your sake.
Is anyone else concerned that there's more to Savathûn's plan than she's letting on?
I hate to admit it, but I agree. She's up to something. She's been especially curious about you.
She asked me where you go when you… dissolve.
Well, that's open to interpretation, even among Ghosts!
Personally, I think we decompile into a quantum superposition… like a sentient frequency.
But unless she's planning to exist in multiple states at once, I can't imagine how that would help her.
The Techeuns study both Light and Darkness, right?
They study paracausal forces, in whatever form they manifest.
And they don't shy away from the truth, even if it comes from the Darkness.
What's your point, Crow?
Savathûn knows the truth about the Black Fleet. Why shouldn't we learn from her, even if she's a creature of Darkness?
If you're counting on getting the truth from the Hive god of deceit, you're already lying to yourself.
Xivu Arath is determined to destroy Savathûn. No matter how much it costs her.
Her obsession is beyond sword logic. This seems… personal.
The bond between siblings surpasses any form of logic.
I once had a sister myself. She was a Techeun, just like those we're rescuing.
She was killed in the Raze of Amethyst. I still see her in my dreams and meditations.
But sentiment has no place in this fight. Savathûn understands that. I hope Mara does too.
We've never seen Hive utilizing Stasis. Don't you find that strange?
I've never seen a Warlock pull out a Golden Gun either.
You may be a smart-ass, but you might also have made an unintentionally good point.
Perhaps something about the Hive prevents them from wielding Stasis.
I don't think anything is that simple. But I feel like when we try to understand the Darkness, we come up short.
We're children trying to understand why the moon glows in the dark. We don't know what we don't know.
Are you there, Petra? I have a request.
Anything, my queen.
I would request… your patience.
But my queen, I would find it gauche to offer the selfsame gift, time and again.
Yes, but I do humbly request it nonetheless.
Mm. My queen asks, and I have no choice but to provide.
I don't care what Mara Sov thinks, this feels like it might be a bad idea.
I'm worried, too, but she has all the leverage.
Without her, Osiris—the REAL Osiris—may be lost forever.
If he isn't already dead.
We need to have hope, otherwise… I… I don't know what Saint has left.
Petra… I just realized where I recognize you from. Spider's place on the Tangled Shore.
Could be. He and I worked together when our desires aligned.
What did he do to keep you coming back? Put a bomb in a friend of yours?
Y'know, he sent me a message recently. Something about bringing a bird back to its nest?
Every time I come to the Dreaming City, it feels like I never left.
Perhaps something here calls to you. Something deeper than identity. Deeper than memory.
Guardians leave their pasts behind by necessity… and by choice. We can only be one person at a time.
To my point. Identities may change, but the person behind them remains the same.
Whoever I was felt at home here… But I'm not him anymore. The Tower is my home now.
Glint. If you had to describe the way the Spider treated Crow in a single word, what word would that be?
Ah, well, the Spider is a valued member of the Shore's, uh, ecosystem. I wouldn't want to offend.
The Spider is not here.
Well, I… I would say… horrible. He was horrible. He tortured Crow, demeaned him, treated him like a possession—
That's enough. I have all the confirmation I need.
Now that we have a moment to pause… I would like to apologize for Crow's behavior. He should not have tried to gain access to Savathûn.
I see my brother's boyish antics in his every move. He is... a familiar pain.
He's also an outstanding Guardian. His willingness to sacrifice himself to stop Xivu Arath, to save Zavala.
He is as brave as he is frustrating.
That he is.
Does it bother you in the slightest to kill Scorn, Crow?
It does, actually. I feel a deep sadness for them. In a way, they remind me of myself.
That probably comes from your time with the Eliksni. I think Spider still misses you.
The Spider, the Scorn, and now Savathûn? You're an atrocious judge of character.
I liked you right away, so maybe you're right.
Petra, is Queen Mara's magic powerful enough to keep us safe from Savathûn?
Yes. Not even a Hive god could break out of that prison.
That's a relief. And she's not going to get tricked or anything, right?
Glint, I trust Mara to keep her monster caged. And I hope you'll do the same.
Okay. Sorry, do you mean that you hope I'll trust her, or that I'll…
You know exactly what I mean.
Well done, Guardian. The Reefborn thank you.
If we are to survive the coming storm, the Tower and the Dreaming City must stand united.
We'll hold the Blind Well together. As we open more Ley Lines, we can start exfiltrating our lost Techeuns.
Once my coven is reassembled, we'll exorcise Savathûn's worm and put an end to her lies. Once and for all.
Petra, how exactly would Xivu Arath gain access to these Ley Lines?
In theory, she could enter anywhere the lines pass through an Ascendant Realm.
Oh, we chased the High Celebrant through one of those once! Crow fell into an abyss. It was quite the adventure!
I’m sure it was. And Mara has entrusted me to protect the Reef from exactly that kind of adventure.
Petra, what's the bleed-through at the Guardian's location?
It’s growing. It’s slow, but it’s making progress every day. We have to keep fighting.
Bleed through?
As the Ley Lines are held open, echoes of the Ascendant Plane slowly creep into our world.
That doesn’t sound good.
You have a gift for understatement.
Queen Mara, how is it you and the Techeuns can use the Ley Lines to travel?
We can manipulate the lines—influence them with our paracausal abilities.
Me, I prefer to use causal abilities: I see one of Xivu Arath’s minions, I cause it to die.
Petra, I believe I asked you to stop making that joke.
That you did, my queen. That you certainly did.
The Guardian succeeded. If they keep this up, Xivu Arath won't be able to use the Blind Well to do… whatever it is it does.
If the Blind Well falls, our enemies could use it to gain access to all Ley Lines.
Aren't they in the Ascendant Realms around here already?
You misunderstand. All Ley Lines, everywhere. Xivu Arath's forces filling the veins of reality, moving across the galaxy in a heartbeat. An infection of war.
Then I will defend the Blind Well with all I have.
What do you think Savathûn is going to do after she's freed from her worm?
What happens to Savathûn is not your concern.
She helped the Guardian liberate me from Spider. I owe her.
Feel sort of a kinship with her, do you?
It’s not like that.
For your sake, it had better not be.
So, Crow. I heard you disobeyed a direct order from the Vanguard when you first pursued Osiris here.
Sometimes it’s better to ask for forgiveness than permission.
Besides, the Vanguard isn’t always right.
Is that so?
Zavala told me to stand down when Mithrax brought House Light to the City, but if I’d been there…
I won’t make the same mistake twice.
You sound like Lord Saladin.
Crow… I think I can… feel her, sometimes.
Savath��n?
Yes. It's as if she's reaching out to me... delicately, like an insect waving its antennae.
A word of advice: don't wave back.
Crow, how does it feel to be working with other Awoken?
Petra and Mara certainly are different than Zavala. They're a touch… hm, prickly.
Can't argue with that. I just wondered if you feel more comfortable around your people.
Eh, it's a little hard to identify with magic people who arose from a paracausal black hole.
You've all lived through different hardships. But you might have more in common than you think.
Glint. How did you decide your Guardian was the right one?
Well, I had been searching for years for my Guardian—longer than most other Ghosts. But the moment I found him, I knew he was the one.
Are you sure you couldn't have searched for just a bit longer?
Nope!
Petra, I've noticed the Awoken don’t have the same reverence for the Light as Humans. Why is that?
Most Humans think the world only works one way. That Light is good, and Darkness is evil.
That may not always be true, but it's most often the case.
The Light is a weapon, but it's also a tool. You know that. So do the Splicers.
Well, Mara says that the same is true of the Darkness. But the only Human who seems to understand that is Eris Morn.
Believe me, you'll need more than the Light to defeat what's coming.
Petra, I heard you used to be a Corsair. That's like, what? The elite Awoken special forces?
Yes, before I became part of the queen's guard.
Ah, that means now you mainly guard the queen?
It means anyone who threatens Queen Mara, or the Reef, will have to deal with me.
Makes sense. I don't plan on doing either of those things, so… I should be fine.
Well done. The Techeuns will be invaluable in the fight against the Black Fleet.
Good. We need all the help we can get.
And… what do the Techeuns do, exactly? I'm asking for a friend.
They're experts in paracausal forces, and keepers of the Distributary's secrets.
If anyone can intuit the means and ways of the Black Fleet, it will be them.
Ikora, I've been thinking about some things Osiris— [grunts] Savathûn asked me to do.
I assume these weren't in any official reports. What did she want?
Dead Ghosts—a handful from Spider's personal collection.
I see. We didn't find any when we searched Saint and Osiris's home in the City.
Nevertheless, it's troubling.
Curious. Savathûn orchestrates an attempted invasion of the Last City by the Vex. Her plan… [grunts] fails?
No. A smoke screen. Her plan succeeds.
But then... something goes wrong. She has to flee to the Dreaming City, parleys with the queen.
We know Xivu Arath wasn't coordinating with Savathûn. She was pursuing her…
Working through a tactical analysis, Petra?
What? Ah, yes. Yes. Just trying to understand what happened between the events on Earth and here.
I have some suspicions I'll share with you later.
I've been to the Dreaming City before, but I don't know if I've ever really taken time to appreciate it until now.
There is so much more than you've seen. And all of that? It pales to what resides in the Distributary.
You could stay… if you wanted. I could show you.
I'm not sure the Vanguard would... I don't know.
There's no need to decide now. Think it over.
You deserve to know your people's history.
So, Petra. We Guardians have this tradition—it started with a good friend. Drinks! After a successful operation.
What makes you think, even for a moment, I'd be interested in that?
Because you seem like you could use a break. Maybe blow off a little steam?
No.
But—but you haven't even heard where—Petra?
Hello?
Must be a bad signal.
Petra, what assistance has the Spider offered us in this endeavor?
None, my queen.
I am not surprised. When you're through there, we will discuss this.
Oh, I wholeheartedly agree.
The Spider may claim to be the Shore's only law, but there is one ruler of the Reef. It's time we remind him of that fact.
Xivu Arath will stop at nothing to destroy her sister.
Hard to believe siblings could harbor that much hatred for each other.
Our loved ones inspire us. But that inspiration takes many forms, not all of them positive.
The Eliksni have a saying: "The friendly knife is sharpest." Maybe that's true.
I think so. We can ask Osiris about it, when we find him.
You're quite the fighter, Petra. I'll be sure to stay on your good side.
I don't have a good side. And if I did, you wouldn’t be on it.
Hm, maybe you just can't see it because your good side… is also your blind side.
Oh no.
Nobody's more blind than you… Crow. Even I can see that.
Come in, Crow. How's it going down there?
Quite well. We're getting the information we need, piece by piece.
I was more interested in how you're getting along with Mara and Petra.
I… I know how to behave around people. You don't have to keep an eye on me.
Hmm. I've had my eye on you for longer than you know. Ikora out.
Glint… do you know if Ikora…
I'd suggest you not even think about it.
Mara… Queen Mara, are you there?
Always.
I met an Awoken once who called me Reefborn…
Said it was because of how I spoke and moved. I didn't really know what that meant until I met you.
I am not Reefborn.
Oh, I just assumed… I'm sorry. F–Forgive me.
Perhaps it is fortunate that Crow has spread his wings. I do not know how he'd respond to the Scorn after what Savathûn has shown him.
Agreed. He needs time to comes to terms with Uldren's involvement in their creation.
The Scorn's continued presence here can't be all about the Ether. There must be a larger strategy at play.
Strategy is not the Scorn's greatest asset.
Their uncommon focus belies a greater will than we've seen before.
If your compass led us here, then we're about to have visitors.
The compass operates beyond a level of causality. Perhaps even beyond the bounds of time.
It has what some might call "intuition."
Are the Ley Lines natural phenomena, or something the Awoken created?
They're naturally occurring paracausal forces that predate the Awoken.
The only entities that might know their true origin and makeup are the Nine. But I don't think they're telling.
As strange as it sounds, we may have stumbled into a beneficial situation here.
How so? Your Techeuns are scattered, and the Dreaming City is on the verge of being overrun.
Yes, but at least we're fighting on our terms. With Savathûn as bait, Xivu Arath has come to us, on our field of choice.
There's Scorn inbound.
It's unclear whether they're coordinating with Xivu Arath's forces or just taking advantage of the chaos.
We can't risk them poisoning the Blind Well with Dark Ether. Let's clear them out.
We've got to prevent the Scorn from poisoning the Ley Lines. Destroy the Ether before they can harvest it.
Are we sure there's no way to save that Ether? I know a lot of Eliksni on the Shore who could really use it.
This is no time for sympathy. We're here to save the Dreaming City, not the Eliksni.
Have you discovered any evidence of coordination between the Scorn and Xivu Arath?
I imagine that the leader of the Hidden knows better than any of us.
I heard so many stories about the Scorn during my time with Spider, but never how they came to be.
How things came to be is less important than accepting them for what they are.
Hidden reports indicate reduced Hive activity throughout the system.
Xivu Arath's forces are poised in the Ascendant Plane, waiting to burst through the Blind Well.
I doubt Xivu Arath knows what Queen Mara is planning, but she knows that every day it grows nearer.
She'll redouble her efforts, I'm sure. And with Crow gone, we're more vulnerable than before.
As Xivu Arath consolidates power, we're likely to face more coordinated resistance.
I expect the full weight of her force to land on the day of the ritual.
We’ll be ready when it does.
Your compass's work is almost done. We need to defend the Blind Well for just awhile longer.
And then Savathûn will kneel before the one true Queen of the Reef.
With each Ley Line we restore, we get closer to our lost Techeuns.
And Xivu Arath's army gets closer to us.
Xivu Arath must be terrified of what Savathûn might say.
She's not the only one. I sense the same fear from you.
My coven grows daily. But we must hold the Blind Well awhile longer.
Between our Light and your mystical knowledge, we're pretty unbreakable. Right, cousin?
I'm not your cousin, Lightbearer.
The compass points unerringly to your goals, and clears obstacles from your path by the strength of your will.
It will discover our lost Techeuns, when you will it.
If we secure the Techeuns, and remove Savathûn's worm, will that end the curse on the Dreaming City?
It's a necessary step, but unfortunately, not sufficient.
Welcome back to the Blind Well, Guardian. It enables transit between this reality and the Ascendant Plane, using paracausal Ley Lines.
Unfortunately, this gate opens both ways. Xivu Arath, Hive god of war, is trying to secure it for an invasion of the Dreaming City so she can capture Savathûn.
We must hold this location at all costs. Glad to have you along, Guardian.
The attacks against the Blind Well have become stronger lately.
Is Xivu Arath trying to rescue Savathûn?
Xivu Arath has plans for her sister. They do not involve a rescue.
Your compass was made in the Distributary to guide those who departed.
If Xivu Arath were to control it, nothing would stop her army from flooding the city.
This place has such a… unique vibration. The air hums with energy.
The paracausal forces that converge here are mighty. They will increase as you open more Ley Lines.
By stabilizing the Ley Lines, aren't we enabling Xivu Arath's forces?
We are. But we also enable our rescue efforts. Nothing is won without risk.
Xivu Arath will never relent, as long as you possess her sister.
What does she want with Savathûn?
The Witch Queen's importance stretches beyond the Hive's politics. There are greater forces at play.

Collection.Caption: Your compass has led us this far, Guardian. Preserve it until the ritual, and nothing will stand against us.
The Scorn have regrouped. Protect your compass and prepare for battle!
Secure your compass, Guardian. I sense a tide of Dark Ether rushing toward us.
We've got Scorn inbound, Guardian. Better keep your compass safe.
The Blind Well is about to be attacked. Guard the compass and prepare to defend yourselves.

Sequence.Caption: With the new Ley Lines open, the Scorn's Dark Ether will spread even more quickly.
We can't let them poison the Blind Well. Defend it at all costs!

Collection.Caption: Take your compass back. But be prepared for some retaliation.
We've got incoming. Keep your compass safe until after the shooting stops.
I sense a Scorn closing in. Retrieve your compass and prepare for battle.
Push back the Taken, but focus on their leadership. We need those Taken Essences.
Physical destruction alone will not deter the Taken. Their Essences must be secured.
Secure those Taken Essences, Guardian. It's the only thing that will push them back.
Bank the Taken Essences to close their rifts and stabilize the area.
Take down their leadership, and secure as many Taken Essences as you can.
The Taken fight without fear. But their Essences are their weakness. Bank them on sight.
Taken Essences are the key to this fight. Bank them to repel the assault.

Sequence.Caption: Hold off the Taken as best you can.
Once their leadership arrives, put them down and bank their Taken Essence.
That should close the rifts and secure the area.

Collection.Caption: Destroy as many Taken as you can. When one of their leaders drops Taken Essence, bank it to limit their influence.
Holding Taken Essence will feel strangely powerful. Bank as many as needed to end the assault.
The strongest Taken yield their Essences. Retrieve them to close the rifts.
We've seen Scorn and Taken in this area, but never at the same time. It makes me suspect a coordinated alliance.

Sequence.Caption: The coming attack could destabilize the Blind Well's energy regulation system.
If we lose the regulators, there's no telling how the Blind Well will react, or how Xivu Arath will take advantage.
The Scorn and Taken are alternating assaults here.
With a prize as big as your paracausal batteries at stake, I'm surprised by their restraint.
We've seen both Scorn and Taken in this area. That indicates at least a nonaggression pact, if not outright cooperation.
I suspect it's a case of mutual interests. Savathûn is the enemy of everyone's enemy.
These batteries are heavy, Petra. A little teamwork will go a long way.
I'm not opposed to teamwork, if I trust my teammates.
The Ley Lines convey so much power. How can you handle it safely?
That's what the regulators are for. Without them, the Blind Well would be dangerously unstable.
Then I guess we'd better replace those batteries.
We need to replace the batteries that charge the Blind Well's energy regulators. But first, we need to secure the area.
Luckily for us, the batteries are charged with paracausal energy. They'll give you a useful aura against our enemies.
It will take strength and teamwork to get this done, Guardian. Good luck.
The energy of the Ley Lines is too great for the Blind Well to handle all at once.
Let's install those batteries and clear out all hostiles.
We need to replace the batteries for the Blind Well's regulators.
They're dense with paracausal energy, so it'll take teamwork to get them installed.
Shouldn't be too difficult. How heavy could they be?
We need to reinstall the batteries for the Blind Well's regulators.
Fair warning: the batteries look small, but the amount of energy they contain is massive. They'll be heavier than expected.
I'm sure we can carry them in shifts. Many hands make the Light work, right?
